INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_CHARITY_PEDIA', 'The word "charity" comes from the Old French word "charité" which, in turn, was derived from the Latin "caritas".[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]The practice of charity means the voluntary giving of help to those in need who are not related to the giver, though the original meaning is more involved with the concepts of preciousness, dearness, high price. Charitable giving is done directly or by means of a charitable trust or other worthy cause. These institutions evolved to carry out the labor of assisting the poor, and came to be called, called ''charities''. In modern times ''charities'' provide the bulk of charitable giving, in terms of monetary value. The types of charities include orphanages, food banks, religious institutes dedicated to care of the poor, hospitals, organizations that visit the homebound and imprisoned, and many others.', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_INSPIRATION', 'Inspiration', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_INSPIRATION_HELP', '[ICON_TEAM_7] Free Great Prophet: +1', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_INSPIRATION_PEDIA', 'The word "inspiration" comes from the Latin noun inspiratio and from the verb inspirare. Inspirare is a compound term resulting from the Latin prefix in (inside, into) and the verb spirare (to breathe).[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]In classic Roman times, inspirare had already come to mean "to breathe deeply" and assumed also the figurative sense of "to instill [something] in the heart or in the mind of someone".[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Hence ''inspiration'' refers to an unconscious burst of creativity in a literary, musical, or other artistic endeavour. The concept has origins in both Hellenism and Hebraism. The Greeks believed that inspiration came from the muses, as well as the gods Apollo and Dionysus. Similarly, in the Ancient Norse religions, inspiration derives from the gods, such as Odin. Inspiration is also a divine matter in Hebrew poetics. In the Book of Amosthe prophet speaks of being overwhelmed by God''s voice and compelled to speak. In Christianity, inspiration is a gift of the Holy Spirit.', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_TOLERANCE', 'Tolerance', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_TOLERANCE_HELP', '[ICON_HAPPINESS_1] City Happiness: +1 per Religious Building[NEWLINE][ICON_PEACE] Cities with multiple religions also get the Pantheon bonus of the city''s second most popular religion.', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_TOLERANCE_PEDIA', 'Tolerance or toleration is "the practice of deliberately allowing or permitting a thing of which one disapproves. One can meaningfully speak of tolerating, ie of allowing or permitting, only if one is in a position to disallow”. It has also been defined as "to bear or endure" or "to nourish, sustain or preserve". Toleration may signify “no more than forbearance and the permission given by the adherents of a dominant religion for other religions to exist, even though the latter are looked on with disapproval as inferior, mistaken or harmful”[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Tolerance is an attitude of mind that implies non-judgmental acceptance of different lifestyles or beliefs, whereas toleration implies putting up with something that one disapproves of.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Historic examples of ''tolerance'' abound. For instance in an act of tolerance, the Persian king Cyrus the Great was believed to have released the Jews from captivity in 539–530 BC, and permitted their return to their homeland.', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_UNITY', 'Unity', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_UNITY_HELP', '[ICON_GOLDEN_AGE] Golden Age Turns: 10[NEWLINE][ICON_GOLDEN_AGE] Golden Ages require 25% less [ICON_HAPPINESS_1] National Happiness', '', '');
INSERT INTO Cep_Language_EN_US (DateModified, Tag, Text, Gender, Plurality) VALUES (date('2013-12-5'), 'TXT_KEY_POLICY_UNITY_PEDIA', 'Unity refers to the ties in a society that bind people to one another. The term is generally employed in sociology and the other social sciences.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]In simple societies it may be mainly based around kinship and shared values. In more complex societies there are various theories as to what contributes to a sense of social solidarity.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]This brings in the associated term of ''solidarity'' of which it is said:[NEWLINE]"Solidarity does not assume that our struggles are the same struggles, or that our pain is the same pain, or that our hope is for the same future. Solidarity involves commitment, and work, as well as the recognition that even if we do not have the same feelings, or the same lives, or the same bodies, we do live on common ground." - Sara Ahmed', '', '');
